# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: vlang
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:vlang/compiled-language] Informally, a **compiled language** is a programming language that is usually implemented with a compiler rather than an interpreter.
[src:vlang/compiled-language] Because any language can theoretically be either compiled or interpreted, the term lacks clarity: compilation and interpretation are properties of a programming language implementation, not of a programming language.
[src:vlang/compiled-language] Some languages have both compilers and interpreters.
[src:vlang/compiled-language] Furthermore, a single implementation can involve both a compiler and an interpreter.
[src:vlang/compiled-language] For example, in some environments, source code is first compiled to an intermediate form (e.g., bytecode), which is then interpreted by an application virtual machine.
[src:vlang/compiled-language] In other environments, a just-in-time compiler selectively compiles some code at runtime, blurring the distinction further.
[src:vlang/memory-safety] Memory errors were first considered in the context of resource management (computing) and time-sharing systems, in an effort to avoid problems such as fork bombs.
[src:vlang/memory-safety] Developments were mostly theoretical until the Morris worm, which exploited a buffer overflow in fingerd.
[src:vlang/memory-safety] The field of computer security developed quickly thereafter, escalating with multitudes of new attacks such as the return-to-libc attack and defense techniques such as the non-executable stack and address space layout randomization.
[src:vlang/memory-safety] Randomization prevents most buffer overflow attacks and requires the attacker to use heap spraying or other application-dependent methods to obtain addresses, although its adoption has been slow.
[src:vlang/memory-safety] However, deployments of the technology are typically limited to randomizing libraries and the location of the stack.
[src:vlang/memory-safety] In 2019, a Microsoft security engineer reported that 70% of all security vulnerabilities were caused by memory safety issues.
[src:vlang/memory-safety] In 2020, a team at Google similarly reported that 70% of all "severe security bugs" in Chromium were caused by memory safety problems.
[src:vlang/memory-safety] Many other high-profile vulnerabilities and exploits in critical software have ultimately stemmed from a lack of memory safety, including Heartbleed and a long-standing privilege escalation bug in sudo.
[src:vlang/memory-safety] The pervasiveness and severity of vulnerabilities and exploits arising from memory safety issues have led several security researchers to describe identifying memory safety issues as "shooting fish in a barrel".
[src:vlang/memory-safety] Some modern high-level programming languages are memory-safe by default, though not completely since they only check their own code and not the system they interact with.
[src:vlang/memory-safety] Automatic memory management in the form of garbage collection is the most common technique for preventing some of the memory safety problems, since it prevents common memory safety errors like use-after-free for all data allocated within the language runtime.
[src:vlang/memory-safety] However, the performance overhead of garbage collection makes these languages unsuitable for certain performance-critical applications.
[src:vlang/memory-safety] For languages that use manual memory management, memory safety is not usually guaranteed by the runtime.
[src:vlang/memory-safety] Instead, memory safety properties must either be guaranteed by the compiler via static program analysis and automated theorem proving or carefully managed by the programmer at runtime.
[src:vlang/memory-safety] For example, the Rust programming language implements a borrow checker to ensure memory safety, while C and C++ provide no memory safety guarantees.
[src:vlang/memory-safety] The substantial amount of software written in C and C++ has motivated the development of external static analysis tools like Coverity, which offers static memory analysis for C.
[src:vlang/memory-safety] DieHard, its redesign DieHarder, and the Allinea Distributed Debugging Tool are special heap allocators that allocate objects in their own random virtual memory page, allowing invalid reads and writes to be stopped and debugged at the exact instruction that causes them.
[src:vlang/memory-safety] Protection relies upon hardware memory protection and thus overhead is typically not substantial, although it can grow significantly if the program makes heavy use of allocation.
[src:vlang/memory-safety] Randomization provides only probabilistic protection against memory errors, but can often be easily implemented in existing software by relinking the binary.
[src:vlang/memory-safety] The memcheck tool of Valgrind uses an instruction set simulator and runs the compiled program in a memory-checking virtual machine, providing guaranteed detection of a subset of runtime memory errors.
[src:vlang/memory-safety] However, it typically slows the program down by a factor of 40, and furthermore must be explicitly informed of custom memory allocators.
[src:vlang/memory-safety] With access to the source code, libraries exist that collect and track legitimate values for pointers ("metadata") and check each pointer access against the metadata for validity, such as the Boehm garbage collector.
[src:vlang/memory-safety] In general, memory safety can be safely assured using tracing garbage collection and the insertion of runtime checks on every memory access; this approach has overhead, but less than that of Valgrind.
[src:vlang/memory-safety] All garbage-collected languages take this approach.
[src:vlang/memory-safety] For C and C++, many tools exist that perform a compile-time transformation of the code to do memory safety checks at runtime, such as CheckPointer and AddressSanitizer which imposes an average slowdown factor of 2.
[src:vlang/memory-safety] BoundWarden is a new spatial memory enforcement approach that utilizes a combination of compile-time transformation and runtime concurrent monitoring techniques.
[src:vlang/memory-safety] Fuzz testing is well-suited for finding memory safety bugs and is often used in combination with dynamic checkers such as AddressSanitizer.
[src:vlang/memory-safety] Some lists may also include **race conditions** (concurrent reads/writes to shared memory) as being part of memory safety (e.g., for access control).
[src:vlang/memory-safety] The Rust programming language prevents many kinds of memory-based race conditions by default, because it ensures there is at most one writer *or* one or more readers.
[src:vlang/memory-safety] Many other programming languages, such as Java, do *not* automatically prevent memory-based race conditions, yet are still generally considered "memory safe" languages.
[src:vlang/memory-safety] Therefore, countering race conditions is generally *not* considered necessary for a language to be considered memory safe.
[src:vlang/systems-programming] Systems programming requires a great degree of hardware awareness.
[src:vlang/systems-programming] Its goal is to achieve efficient use of available resources, either because the software itself is performance-critical or because even small efficiency improvements directly transform into significant savings of time or money.
[src:vlang/systems-programming] In systems programming, often limited programming facilities are available.
[src:vlang/systems-programming] The use of automatic garbage collection is not common and debugging is sometimes hard to do.
[src:vlang/systems-programming] The runtime library, if available at all, is usually far less powerful, and does less error checking.
[src:vlang/systems-programming] Because of those limitations, monitoring and logging are often used; operating systems may have extremely elaborate logging subsystems.
[src:vlang/systems-programming] Implementing certain parts in operating systems and networking requires systems programming, for example implementing paging (virtual memory) or a device driver for an operating system.
[src:vlang/systems-programming] Originally systems programmers invariably wrote in assembly language.
[src:vlang/systems-programming] Experiments with hardware support in high level languages in the late 1960s led to such languages as PL/S, BLISS, BCPL, and extended ALGOL for Burroughs Large Systems.
[src:vlang/systems-programming] Forth also has applications as a systems language.
[src:vlang/systems-programming] In the 1970s, C became widespread, aided by the growth of Unix.
[src:vlang/systems-programming] More recently a subset of C++ called Embedded C++ has seen some use, for instance it is used in the I/O Kit drivers of macOS.
[src:vlang/systems-programming] Engineers working at Google created Go in 2007 to address developer productivity in large distributed systems, with developer-focused features such as Concurrency, Garbage Collection, and faster program compilation than C and C++.
[src:vlang/systems-programming] In 2015 Rust came out, a general-purpose programming language often used in systems programming.
[src:vlang/systems-programming] Rust was designed with memory safety in mind and to be as performant as C and C++.
[src:vlang/systems-programming] For historical reasons, some organizations use the term *systems programmer* to describe a job function which would be more accurately termed systems administrator.
[src:vlang/systems-programming] This is particularly true in organizations whose computer resources have historically been dominated by mainframes, although the term is even used to describe job functions which do not involve mainframes.
[src:vlang/systems-programming] This usage arose because administration of IBM mainframes often involved the writing of custom assembler code (IBM's Basic Assembly Language (BAL)), which integrated with the operating system such as OS/MVS, DOS/VSE or VM/CMS.
[src:vlang/systems-programming] Indeed, some IBM software products had substantial code contributions from customer programming staff.
[src:vlang/systems-programming] This type of programming is progressively less common, and increasingly done in C rather than Assembly, but the term *systems programmer* is still used as the de-facto job title for staff administering IBM mainframes even in cases where they do not regularly engage in systems programming activities.
[src:vlang/v-programming-language] The goals of V include ease of use, readability, and maintainability.
[src:vlang/v-programming-language] The new language was created as a result of frustration with existing languages being used for personal projects.
[src:vlang/v-programming-language] It was originally intended for personal use, but after being mentioned publicly and increasing interest, it was decided to make it public.
[src:vlang/v-programming-language] V was initially created to develop a desktop messaging client named Volt.
[src:vlang/v-programming-language] On public release, the compiler was written in V, and could compile itself.
[src:vlang/v-programming-language] Key design goals in creating V were being easy to learn and use, higher readability, fast compiling, increased safety, efficient development, cross-platform usability, improved C interoperability, better error handling, modern features, and more maintainable software.
[src:vlang/v-programming-language] V is developed, maintained, and released through GitHub by developers and contributors internationally.
[src:vlang/v-programming-language] In 2025, V started being ranked on the TIOBE index.
[src:vlang/v-programming-language] V has policies to facilitate memory-safety, speed, and secure code, including various default features for greater program safety.
[src:vlang/v-programming-language] It employs bounds checking, to guard against out of bounds use of variables.
[src:vlang/v-programming-language] Option/result types are used, where the option data type (`?`) can be represented by `none` (among possible choices) and the result type (`!`) can handle any returned errors.
[src:vlang/v-programming-language] To ensure greater safety, error checking is mandatory.
[src:vlang/v-programming-language] By default, the following are immutable: variables, structs, and function arguments.
[src:vlang/v-programming-language] This includes string values are immutable, so elements cannot be mutated.
[src:vlang/v-programming-language] Other protections, which are the default for the language, are: no use of undefined values, variable shadowing, null pointers (unless marked as unsafe), or global variables (unless enabled via flag).
[src:vlang/v-programming-language] V uses value types and string buffers to reduce memory allocations.
[src:vlang/v-programming-language] The language can be compiled to human-readable C, and in executing and compiling, is considered as fast.
[src:vlang/v-programming-language] Manual memory management via disabling the garbage collector.
[src:vlang/v-programming-language] Autofree, which is experimental, for invoking the necessary calls to automatically release objects while compiling.
[src:vlang/v-programming-language] V supports a source-to-source compiler (transpiler) and can translate C code into V.
[src:vlang/v-programming-language] Working translators are also being developed for Go, JavaScript, and WebAssembly.
[src:vlang/v-programming-language] Variables are immutable by default and are defined using `:=` and a value.
[src:vlang/v-programming-language] Use the `mut` reserved word (keyword) to make them mutable.
[src:vlang/v-programming-language] By default, structs are allocated via stack-based memory allocation (on the stack).
[src:vlang/v-programming-language] Methods in V are functions defined with a receiver argument.
[src:vlang/v-programming-language] The receiver appears in its own argument list between the `fn` keyword and the method name.
[src:vlang/v-programming-language] Methods must be in the same module as the receiver type.
[src:vlang/v-programming-language] The enrolled_status method (below) has a receiver of type `Client` named `x`.
[src:vlang/v-programming-language] The convention is not to use receiver names like self or this, but preferably a short name.
[src:vlang/v-programming-language] Result types may represent an error returned from a function.
[src:vlang/v-programming-language] Option types prepend `?` to the type name: `?Type`.
